column168: On 11/1/16, a 5 gallon steel pail of UN1263 Sur 870 reducer arrived damaged and leaking at the R&L Carriers terminal in Piedmont, SC. column168: On 11/1/16, a 55 gallon steel drum of UN2735 ancamine k 54 arrived dented and punctured at the R&L Carriers terminal in Milwaukee, WI.  The drum had been dented and punctured by an unsecured pallet of freight in transit.  The damaged drum released approximately 1 quart of material to the trailer floor.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site to clean the area and over-pack the drum.  The release was cleaned with granular absorbents and all waste was taken for disposal by the contractor.  The damaged drum was over-packed into a 95 gallon poly drum.  The over-pack was labeled as salvage and with all applicable shipping information.  The over-pack was left on site for R&L personnel to manage.

On 11/01/2016, at the XPO Logistics terminal in Dallas, TX,  it was discovered that a 550 pound cylinder of UN1083 anhydrous trimethylamine was leaking in a trailer.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to respond to the site.  The environmental contractor donned all the proper ppe and entered the trailer.  There it was discovered that the valve had come loose during shipping which resulted in the release of approximately 50 pounds of material.  The valve was re-secured by the contractors and there was no further release of material.  All cylinders were checked to ensure there were no more leaks and all cylinders were verified as secure.  All cylinders continued for shipping.  There were no reported injuries or exposures due to the incident.

column168: On 11/4/2016 at 1426 ERTS was contacted XPO Logistics about a cargo release. It was reported that due to a improper blocking and bracing a 10 gallon metal pail was crushed containing UN1866 "resin solution"  releasing approximately 1 cup to the trailer #3196515 floor. Prior to calling ERTS, terminal personnel cleaned the release by using granular absorbents. They placed the spent absorbents and impacted container into a 12 gallon metal drum and moved to OS&D with a Hazardous-Waste label. There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by this incident.Spills in trailers, concrete docks, containment areas, inside buildings are not into environment and not considered reportable in the state of Florida.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: It was reported that due to a unknown cause, approximately 2 gallons of UN1210 "Printing Ink" was released from (1) 55-gallon steel drum. The trade name of the product was unknown at the time of the call. A contractor was dispatched to assess and clean the release. The contractor determined the cause of the release to be approximately 2 gallons total due to a packaging failure due to a bad seam. The release was contained to the trailer floor and gravel underneath the trailer. The trailer floor was treated with granular absorbents and a water test was conducted to show no leeching was occurring. The impacted drum was overpacked into (1) 65-galllon poly overpack, labeled “salvage,” and continued with shipping. (1) 55-gallon metal drum of non-hazardous waste was generated containing impacted absorbents and pads and spill debris.

On November 3, 2016, XPO Logistics (LDA Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN3265, Lime Away, 8, II (PRO#933859511) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel were unloading a trailer (3177700) from the XSW Terminal, when 1-5 gallon poly pail was discovered to be damaged. It appeared that the pail fell over due to no blocking and bracing during transit. Approximately 1 gallon of product has been released to the trailer floor. Contractor indicated that there are 2 cases with 4-1 gallon poly cans are in the cases. Contractor indicated that the boxes appeared to have fallen during transit. Contractor indicated that the boxes appeared to be saturated. Contractor indicated that the cans don't appear to be punctured at this time. Contractor indicated that approximately 1 gallon of product has been lost due to leaking from the caps when the cases had fallen over during transit. Contractor used "Color Safe" to neutralize impacted cardboard and bottles. Contractor indicated that the release resulting from the containers being tipped on the side leaking from the caps. Contractor wiped down the cans and terminal personnel want to salvage product.Contractor generated 1-55 gallon poly drum of neutralized absorbents, ppe and debris to be staged on site in OS & D. All the poly jugs were wiped down, tightened and left for salvage.

Upon arrival at the Veolia ten-day in transit facility located in Blaine, MN, A Veolia driver observed that there was a small amount of liquid on the floor of the trailer. Upon further investigation, it was identified that one of the seven IBC's being transported had shifted slightly on the pallet it was on during transit. This allowed a small amount of liquid to release from the containers which were only supposed to contain solids. The spill, which did not exit the trailer, was contained and cleaned up using absorbent material. The IBC's positioning was corrected and it was secured on the pallet.
column169: The investigation of this incident revealed that the IBC's used for this shipment were not UN specification packaging. In addition, the waste placed into the packages was supposed to be 100% solids. Both items were reviewed with the shipper. The shipper agreed to make process changes to eliminate free liquids from this wastestream. In addition, they will check with their IBC vendor to ensure future shipments are packaged in the proper UN specification packages.

column168: WHEN THE DOCK PLATE WAS EXTENDED TO ALLOW FOR THE LOADING OF THE EXTRA PIECE, THE CORNER OF THE DOCK PLATE CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE DRUM. THIS CONTACT CAUSED A HOLE APPROX. 1/4" IN DIAMETER ON THE BOTTOM THIRD OF THE DRUM. THE DRUM LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 10 SECONDS BEFORE IT WAS LAID ON ITS SIDE WITH THE HOLE UP TO STOP IT FROM LEAKING FURTHER. APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL LEAKED OUT OF THE DRUM ONTO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER, DOCK, AND DOWN INTO THE CATCH BASIN. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP USING SPILL PADS AND ABSORBENT.
column169: IN THE EVENT THAT A LOADED TRAILER MUST HAVE THE DOCK PLATE EXTENDED AGAIN, ENSURE THAT THERE IS ENOUGH SPACE (NO LESS THAN 12") BETWEEN THE LAST ROW OF DRUMS AND THE END OF THE TRAILER IN ORDER TO ALLOW FOR THE SAFE EXTENSION OF THE DOCK PLATE ONTO THE TRAILER. IF THIS IS NOT THE CASE, THE LAST ROW OF DRUMS IS TO BE REMOVED USING A FORK LIFT AND PARROT BEAKS, SO THAT THE DOCK PLATE CAN BE SAFETY EXTENDED.

column168: JOSE WAS MOVING PALLETS OF IRREGS TO BE LOADED WHEN HE NOTICED THAT THERE WAS LIQUID UNDER THE PALLET. HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR THE SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. I TESTED THE PH OF THE LIQUID IT WAS APPROX 1. I CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING PAIL INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID. I RETESTED THE PH UNTIL THE PH WAS IN THE NEUTRAL RANGE OF 6-9. I THEN USED CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT TO SOLIDIFY ANY REMAINING LIQUID. I SWEPT UP ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS CONTAINERIZED THEM INTO MULTIPLE LINED SPILL TRAYS. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE ALL SOILED ITEMS TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION I FOUND A PUNCTURE HOLE IN THE 5 GALLON BOTTLE.

column168: Car was inspected on 11-2-16 by FRA hazmat inspector Hudon. Car was reported to mechanical dept to have loose fittings on manway. Car was inspected by UPRR Hazmat on 11-9-16. The car was observed to have a liquid release from the manway. Upon further inspection, it was determined that the manway lid was bent. The ears on the lid were bent to an extent where the ears were making contact with the nozzle before the gasket was allowed to seal the fitting. The manway lid gasket was removed and a nozzle gasket was put into place. This allowed for a proper securement of the fitting. The car was released and continued in transport without further incident.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 11-8-2016 I, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE, was called out for a report of car PROX 45406 leaking at our yard in Brewster, OH.  The car inspector found an odor coming from this car as he was inspecting the inbound train.  When I investigated, I found that the liquid valve was leaking through the valve plug.  The valve was tight and still leaking through.  The plug valve was less than tool tight.  I tightened the plug and the leak stopped.  I contacted Markwest and advised them of the leak and they sent Sunpro out to look at the valve at our yard.  They came out on 2-9-2016 and determined that the liquid valve was faulty and needed replaced.  They ordered a new valve.  Sunpro came into our yard on 2-17-2016 and replaced the valve and tested it with nitrogen.  The repaired passed a bubble test. This car was released for service on 2-17-2016.
column169: Better securement procedures need followed.

column168: At 0920 ERTS was notified by Jason Mabee of R&L Carriers - HAG to report a spill. Terminal personnel will place the (4) 1 gallon (2 gallon pails to each box) that were impacted into (1) 55 gallon poly drum, labeled hazardous waste, and placed in OS&D for waste pick up. column168: I, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE, was called to the WLE Mechanical Shop on 11-14-2016 for car GATX 202707 that reported leaking.  The Carmen who were working on the car brakes said they could smell an odor coming from it.  When I investigated, I found that both liquid valves and the vapor valve on the car were leaking.  I tried to tighten the valves to stop the leak but they were already tight.  The valve plugs were less than tool tight.  I tightened all the valve plugs after putting thread sealant on them and the leaks stopped.  I am waiting on home shop disposition and an OTMA from the shipper.

column168: On Nov 15 2016, at 0725, personnel in the CSXT Dalton Yard discovered TCIX16108, a loaded tank car of Sodium Hydroxide Solution, leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and Shintech Lousiana, LLC, Marion Environmental and NRC were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2016-11-15-00062). Marion Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found historic residue around the pressure relief valve. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Steve Polito, 225-685-1199. Contractor personnel determined the valve had already reseated itself and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 700  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100

UPRR yard personnel reported that tank car RCRX 2648 appeared to have smoke coming from the top of the car.  Inspection of the car found approximately one cup of hydrochloric acid on top of the fixed manway cover as well as what appeared to be part of a gasket.  Subsequent inspection of the fittings found a corresponding gap in the gasket below the air valve (approximately one-quarter of the gaskets circular profile was missing).  The car was decontaminated with a baking soda/water solution and secured for the night.      Reagent Chemical (shipper) responded on November 9, 2016, and replaced the defective gasket.  On November 10, 2016, GBW (railcar repair) performed a bubble leak test to allow the car to continue in transportation.

column168: At 1040 on 11/10/2016 ERTS was contacted by Brian Rider from R&L WIL terminal. It was reported that they found a 5 gallon pail of UN1210 had fallen from it's skid onto another, due to improper blocking and bracing. The impact with the other skid creased the seam in the pail which released approximately 2 ounces of material to the trailer floor. Prior to calling ERTS the terminal personnel cleaned the release using granular absorbents. The impacted pail was placed into a 55 gallon drum, placed into OS&D awaiting disposition. The released material and granular absorbents were placed into a 5 gallon pail and placed into OS&D for disposal. Spills in trailers, concrete docks, containment areas, inside buildings are not into environment and not considered reportable, so at this time there is no regulatory reporting required, other than the DOT 5800 due to the PG II of the material. There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by this incident. Chemtrec was notified of the release and issued report number 2016111000098. The SDS was requested from the manufacturer.

column168: On 11/10/16 it was discovered that approximately .5 gallon of UN1210 VWM screen wash had released from 17 steel totes of the material in an R&L Carriers trailer near Wamsutter, WY.  The totes were being shipped as "empty last contained UN1210 printing ink".  The release impacted an asphalt parking lot and no soils, drains or waterways were impacted. An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the area and secure the totes.  The contractor discovered that the bottom caps and valves had not been properly secured prior to shipping causing the release of the residual material.  The valves were all closed and the caps secured with duct tape and zip ties.  The release was cleaned with granular absorbents and all waste was taken for disposal.  After the totes were secured the shipment continued on for transit.

column168: At 0830 on 11/17/2016 ERTS was contacted by Mikel Diaz from XPO LHW. It was reported that as the forklift was moving a skid on the dock, a strap from the skid fell and got caught under the wheels of the lift. When the strap pulled tight it grabbed a 55 gallon poly drum of UN3264 to the loading dock surface. The impact with the concrete ruptured the drum which released approximately 1 gallon of material to the dock floor. During the call, the SDS was reviewed, and the caller indicated that he had no way to neutralize the released material. ERTS advised the caller to place granular absorbents on the spill and cones around it, to keep traffic out of it while a contractor was being dispatched.  Spills in trailers, concrete docks, containment areas, inside buildings are not into environment and not considered reportable, but a DOT 5800 is required for this release due to the PG II of the material. There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by this incident. ERTS is dispatching USES to respond to the site and perform ER cleanup of the release. An ETA of 2 hours was provided. Chemtrec Notification -- 2016111700057. Titan Entry --  LHW-014849.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Valve Open
column168: At approximately 13:40 PTRA Trainmaster Villarreal reported an odor in the vicinity of track 10 at the PTRA Manchester Yard. M&M Protection was notified and dispatched to the scene to determine the source of the odor. With the assistance of the PTRA Safety Director, M&M was able to determine that the leak was coming from DOWX 73083 an empty residue ethyl acrylate tank car.  Further investigation revealed that the one inch vapor line valve cap was not applied and the valve was left partially open allowing vapors to be released. M&M Protection personnel closed the valve and applied the cap. PID and LEL meters did not measure any readings after taking the aforementioned steps. New seals were applied to the protective housing and manway.  The scene was cleared at approximately 16:05

Cynthia accepted the shipment just prior to closing from two gentleman asking to use the Northern Alaska Tours CID.  Tendered by John Peters and another gentleman.  I looked at the shipment as it was being weighed and saw the tool boxes.  I came into the office to specifically ask about any hazmat, lithium ion batteries, ect really questioning them.  Was advised nothing like that in the bags.  Cynthia started screening the 6 duffel bags on the x-ray. The ammo was found in 2 duffel bags.  I went in and called NATC office, trying to get back in touch with the shippers.  They said someone would come out tomorrow (Sat).  Blocked shipment for transport.  On Saturday Nov 26, I contacted ANC Alaska Airlines office for some assistance on UN for ammo.  Was advised to make sure we document pictures and verify nothing else in shipment that shouldn't be.  I advised Cynthia that we needed to open and hand search every piece in the shipment.  I did the 5 red metal toolboxes and Cynthia did the 6 duffel bags.  Nothing was found in the tool boxes, everything questionable was in the bags.  I took pictures and followed ANCFF procedure for reporting via email, which confused me and didn't file this report within the 24hrs.

11/15/2016:  Conrail (CR) Trainmaster M. Little called CR's Risk Management Department to advise that while conducting a routine inspection at CR's Port Richmond Yard, Philadelphia, PA, FRA Hazmat Inspector D. Thrower found tank car OXAX 3320, containing the residue of Combustible Liquid, NOS (2-Ethylhexanol) to be seeping from the bottom outlet valve's closure plug.    CR's Risk Management representatives A. Richter and S. Hart responded and met with FRA Inspector Thrower.  Further inspection of the car found the bottom outlet valve's operating handle not secured and partially in the open position; and the bottom outlet valve's closure plug was less than tool tight.  CR closed the bottom outlet valve and secured the bottom outlet valve closure plug by use of a 24-inch pipe wrench.    Additional exceptions found by Inspector Thrower on the same car noted five (5) of eight (8) manway cover securement bolts not even hand tight; and, three (3) of eight (8) manway cover bolts were not applied.  All manway cover securement bolts were secured tool tight by use of a 24-inch pipe wrench.    Bottom outlet re-examined approximately 20 minutes after securement and found to be secured with no further leak.  Car okayed for movement to original consignee.
column169: During the same day's inspection by the FRA, Inspector Thrower had noted exceptions on the following tank car:    UTLX 209135, residue last contained Combustible Liquid, NOS (2-Ethylhexanol), noted with all eight (8) manway cover securement bolts not even hand tight.  All bolts were secured tool tight by use of a 24-inch pipe wrench, and car was permitted to move to original destination.

column168: We had one of our fuel trucks delivering diesel to one of our card lock sites and just before completion overfilled an above ground bulk tank in containment. The release was immediately reported to our dispatch which activated our spill response group. The driver placed absorbent material in the containment area around the tank. The driver reported an approx. 25 gallons was released into containment. The duration of the release was not timed but an estimate would be less than a minute.
column169: Initial recommendations would be updating our monitoring software and conducting physical gauging on a more consistent basis.

column168: Loose dome lid.     Driver reports: Had to hard break due to traffic.  It caused product to surge, and product leaked out of the dome lid and down side of trailer. SWS crew moved the cleanup efforts to mile marker 197 to wipe down the tanker.  At 1431, clean up complete and everything into the poly drum with the absorbent.    Dome lid was secured and shipment delivered without further incident.

column168: At 1945 on November 4, 2016 an odor was noted by train crews coming from NATX 300200 in the BNSF Northtown yard in Minneapolis, MN.  The area was evacuated within the yard and a BNSF Mechanical responder investigated the odor. Upon inspecting the rail car it was discovered that the vapor valve was partially open and the secondary closure plug was not installed. The responder closed the valve and replaced the secondary closure plug. After testing for leaks with a soap solution and seeing no indication (bubbles) of vapor release, the car was released for movement. The evacuation was lifted and the yard was back to work.
column169: It is recommended that the shipper unloading operations review their operating procedures with the employees to make sure that all fixtures on rail cars are secured prior to leaving their facility.    BNSF takes events like this seriously as it represents product exposures to its employees, the public and interrupts service to all of our customers.

During a routine post trip inspection at a truck stop, a driver transporting a roll-off box containing a hazardous waste sludge noticed liquid dripping out of the rear door.  After placing a spill bucket and absorbent pads on the ground, a response crew was summoned.  The leak was stopped with a foam sealant. The amount spilled onto the ground was cleaned up and placed back into the box.  After the driver's ten hour break, he checked that the leak was still stopped and returned the box to the generator.
column169: The filter cake sludge in the box had not adequately dried and the solidification process was not enough to remove all of the moisture.  The generator will review the process and not ship boxes that contain free liquids in the future

On 11/29/16 at the R&L Carriers terminal in Kennessaw, GA, a 300 gallon steel tote of UN1206 Heptanes was found leaking while unloading a trailer.  The cause of the release was initially unknown.  The tote released approximately 4 gallons of material to the trailer floor and approximately 1 gallon released to the concrete parking lot.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the area and secure the leaking tote.  Upon arrival, the contractor discovered that the bottom valve of the tote was partially open which caused the release.  It was determined that the valve handle was accidentally struck during unloading of the trailer causing it to open slightly.  The valve was closed and secured.  The tote, its seams and closures were inspected and it was determined the source of the release was in fact the open valve.  The impacted areas of trailer floor and concrete were cleaned with granular absorbents.  All waste was taken offsite for disposal.  The tote was secured and continued on for shipping.

column168: On 11/14/2016 in Cloverfield, TX, a Schneider Bulk Carriers DOT 307 trailer carrying UN3256 Nalco EC5351A experienced a release of approximately 20 gallons of material.  The release stemmed from a defective blow out ring on a top wash out cap.  It is unknown how or why the blow out ring on the wash out cap failed.  The release impacted the trailer body and asphalt roadway. No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the area and secure the trailer.  The impacted asphalt and trailer body were cleaned with absorbent pads and granular absorbents.  All impacted absorbents were collected into 55 gallon steel drums and taken for offsite disposal.  A new washout cap was secured in place of the defective cap.  Once the cap was replaced there was no further release when the trailer moved.  The secured trailer continued on for transport.

column168: At 0130 hrs. on 11-8-2016, the midnight car inspector in Brewster yard noticed an odor coming from PROX 45406.  He called the Yardmaster who contacted me, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  I came to look at the car and found that the liquid valve was leaking through the valve plug.  The plug was less than tool tight.  The valve was closed but still leaking through.  I tightened the valve plug and the leak stopped.  We set the car to an isolated track so that it could be repaired. I contacted Markwest who called Sunpro to come out and look at the car.  They found that the valve was defective and they had to order a new one.  They came out a week later and replaced the valve and bubble tested the car and there was no leaks found.  The car was then released for service.
column169: I am not sure that the leak would have been noticed when the car was loaded.

column168: On November 12, 2016 at approximately 15:00 hours personnel along the CSX Main Line in Lebanon Junction, KY noticed an odor in the area of PROX 37129, a residue tank car of liquefied petroleum gas. column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. DURING OFFLOAD, APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF MDI WERE RELEASED TO THE SOIL/GRAVEL LOT AS A RESULT OF A BLOWN HOSE ON THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., INC. VEHICLE. FREE PRODUCT IMPACTED SOIL/GRAVEL SURFACE IN IMMEDIATE AREA AND DID NOT MIGRATE OFF SITE OR THREATEN TO IMPACT STATE WATERS. NORTH SHORE ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. NORTH SHORE ENVIRONMENTAL USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO RECOVER FREE PRODUCT AND EXCAVATED THE IMPACTED SOIL AND GRAVEL FROM THE IMPACTED AREA. APPROXIMATELY 6 YARDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WERE GENERATED DURING RESPONSE. NORTH SHORE ENVIRONMENTAL RESTORED SITE TO PREEXISTING CONDITION AND DISPOSAL WAS COORDINATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

column168: A hazardous, UN1210, Pro Sheen Dowle White -WH 225, 3, II (PRO# 737026866) was released. According to the caller, terminal personnel were unloading a trailer (OA2655) when 1-55 gallon metal drum of product appeared to be leaking. The caller indicated that the drum appears to have a bad seal. Approximately 2 gallon of product has been released to the trailer floor and approximately 1 quart of product has been released to the dock floor.  No soils, drains or waterways have been impacted. Contractors used acetone to clean the dock floor. Contractors generated (1) 85 gallon metal drum of damaged drum with product for waste due to the seals being defecting and continuing to leak. They staged the drum on site pending disposal. (1) 55 gallon metal drum of impacted absorbents and debris will be taken off site for disposal.

column168: Upon commencing to drive away from the point at which he had loaded and secured a roll-off container on to his straight frame truck, it was brought to the driver’s attention that the rear of the roll-off container was dripping from the bottom of the door. The driver immediately placed the roll-off container back onto the ground and further tightened the ratchet chain binders securing the roll-off containers door, stopping the leak.  The driver and facility personnel then donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, and remediated the small spill using absorbent pads and granulated absorbent material. The generated waste from the cleanup was placed in the already manifested roll-off box. The spill was reported to the NJ DEP at 17:59 to operator #76, report number 161121175938.
column169: We discovered that shipper had improperly loaded items with liquid oil residue into a container not designed to transport liquids. In addition, the driver did not adequately inspect the tightness of the roll-off containers rear door ratcheting chain binders. We have asked the shipper to take more care to put the correct waste streams into the correct type of waste containers.  The driver has received retraining on the proper inspection of a roll-off container prior to transportation.

column168: On 11/29/2016, (2) boxes of (12) 14 ounce bottles of UN1790 Rust Go arrived tipped over at the R&L Carriers terminal in Colonial Heights, VA.  The pallet was unsecured causing the freight to shift in transit and fall over.  The fall caused one of the 14 ounce bottles of material to release approximately 1 cup of material through a loose cap.  The release was contained to the cardboard of the 2 boxes and no soils, drains or waterways were impacted.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release.  The impacted cardboard and damaged/impacted bottles of material were containerized and staged on site pending proper profiling and disposal.

column168: BNSF Mechanical identified a release from the top of GBRX700330 during an inbound inspection.  BNSF Mechanical Responders identified the release from the liquid line valve, which required securement.  An OTMA was required for further movement and obtained by the shipper.  United Pumping was contracted to decontaminate the exterior of the tank car for movement to destination.
column169: Inspection of all tank car appurtenances prior to offering for shipment would have identified the loose valve.

column168: CARTERENERGY DRIVER TREVOR WILLIAMS WAS FUELING A GENESEE AND WYOMING RAILROAD LOCOMOTIVE IN THE GWRR SWITCHYARD WITH DF FROM A 4400 GALLON FUEL TANK WAGON (TW) AS DISPATCHED. THERE WAS LIGHT RAIN AND THE AREA WAS DARK WITH AUXILIARY LIGHTING BEING USED ON BACK OF TANK WAGON TO LIGHT UP THE FUELING AREA. TREVOR OBSERVED TANK INVENTORY GAGE ON LOCOMOTIVE NOTING BEGINNING READING OF 360 GALLONS. HE CONNECTED DRY BREAK FUEL NOZZLE FROM TW TO THE LOCOMOTIVE FUEL TANK CONNECTION AND BEGAN FILLING LOCOMOTIVE. TREVOR WAS STANDING AT THE BACK OF THE TW WATCHING TANK GAGE AS NORMAL. AFTER APPX 12 MINUTES DRIVER STATED HE OBSERVED FUEL SPRAYING FROM LOCOMOTIVE TANKS 1.5 INCH DIAMETER OVERFILL PIPE ONTO GRAVEL AREA BESIDE THE LOCOMOTIVE. TREVOR IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF PTO PUMP ON THE TW AND GRABBED SIX EA 2" DIAMETER BY 6’ LONG FUEL ABSORBENT BOOMS FROM THE TW. TREVOR PLACED THEM NEAR A PUDDLE OF RAIN WATER TO PREVENT ANY OF THE DF FROM REACHING THE PUDDLE. TREVOR CONTACTED RODNEY THOMAS GWRR YARD SUPERVISOR AND TARA CAULKINS  CARTERENERGY DISPATCHER TO REPORT THE SPILL. RODNEY ARRIVED WITHIN 2 MINUTES AND ACCESSED THE SITUATION. RODNEY DIRECTED A GWRR BACKHOE OPERATOR TO BEGIN REMOVING GRAVEL AND DIRT THAT HAD ABSORBED THE DF AND PLACED CONTAMINATED PRODUCT ON A PLASTIC TARP. TOTAL QUANTITY REMOVED WAS APPX 5 CUBIC YARDS. RODNEY THAN ORDERED A DUMP TRUCK LOAD OF DIRT AND GRAVEL TO BACKFILL THE HOLE.  AARON SMITH CARTERENERGY'S DALLAS COMMERCIAL SALESMAN CONTACTED THE TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY TO REPORT THE SPILL AND WAS GIVEN REPORT# 20163445. TIM SZIPPL CARTERENERGY SAFETY MANAGER CONTACTED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER TO REPORT THE SPILL AND WAS GIVEN REPORT# 1163637. TAS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES 3929 CALIFORNIA PARKWAY EAST, FT WORTH TX 76119 WAS CONTRACTED TO REMOVE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND DISPOSE OF IAW TEXAS EPA PROCEDURES.
column169: REPAIR DEFECTIVE TANK GAGE, FUELING NOZZLE AND PLACE A PORTABLE 35 GALLON SPILL CONTAINMENT UNDER VENT LINE AS STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES.

column168: Tank car GATX 219735 was involved in a derailment near Ellendale, MN on 11/11/2016. As a result of the derailment the car was punctured mid car left side. The puncture was approximately 4 inches long and 1/2 inch wide. The contents (propane) released for approximately 20 hours until a controlled vent and burn procedure emptied the car's contents.
column169: No additional comments.

column25: URS E&C on behalf of US DOE (SPRU-DP)
column168: SPRU shipped 1 Cargo Tank of water to Perma- Fix North West. While the shipment was in transit , Hubbard Trucking was contacted and advised the water may be a corrosive and to find a safe location and await further instructions. On 11/14/2016 Hubbard Trucking was advised that the shipment was to be reconsigned to DSSI Oak Ridge,TN and new shipping paper was to be sent to the driver. After receipt of the new shipping paper the shipment was delivered in accordance with the reconsignment instruction.
column169: SPRU has revised their procedures and process to avoid similar incidents.

column168: During a routine yard check at the intermediate truck transfer facility, a small drip was noticed coming from a trailer dropped at the dock for unloading.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A drum was found to have a small pinhole leak.  It was over-packed into a suitable salvage container, along with the cleaning compound and absorbent pads used to clean up the spilled material from the trailer floor and concrete containment area.  The spill was reported to the LA State Police--incident number 16-05028.  The shipment was loaded onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The generator was notified to more closely inspect used drums prior to loading and determine compatibility with the material being loaded.

column168: It was reported that (4) - 50 pound plastic bags of UN2680 Lithium Hydroxide were damaged and released approximately 30 pounds of product due to improper blocking and bracing by the previous loading terminal. These bags were torn by dunnage during transit. This release impacted a small portion of the trailer floor.  The released material and debris were containerized into a 5 gallon poly pail by a contractor team and labeled with non-haz waste labels while the 4 damaged bags were placed into a 55 gallon poly drum and labeled as salvageable material.  All waste will be taken off-site once the profile is accepted.

column17: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY
column168: AT 2:09 ON 11-21-2016 A KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) CREW REPORTED SMELLING A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR IN THE KCS YARD AT BEAUMONT, TX. THE ENVIRONMENTAL AND HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE. RESIDUE TANK CAR ACFX 220169, CONTAINING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS FOUND WITH THE B END LIQUID VALVE SLIGHTLY OPEN. THE SECONDARY CLOSURE PLUG WAS ALSO LESS THAN TOO TIGHT. THE VALVE AND THE CLOSURE PLUG WERE CLOSED TOO TIGHT, STOPPING THE LEAK.     FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A BULK SHIPMENT, AKA ONE RESIDUE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED THAT THE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: SPRU SHIPPED 4 TANKERS OF CORROSIVE WATER (12.75 PH) TO SMOKY MOUNTAIN SOLUTIONS. TWO OF THE TANKERS WERE UNLOADED INTO HOLDING TANKING. PH WAS FOUND TO BE CORROSIVE. SAMPLED THE OTHER TWO TANKERS, AND FOUND THEM TO BE CORROSIVE. CONTRACTED SPRU TO INFORM THEM OF THE IMPROPERLY PLACARDED SHIPMENTS. THEY CONTACTED DSSI OF OAK RIDGE TO SEE IF THEY COULD ADJUST THE PH. DSSI WAS CAPABLE OF ADJUSTING THE PH. SPRU SENT PROPER SHIPPING DOCUMENTS TO DSSI, TO ALLOW THEM TO SHIP THE TANKERS FROM SMOKY MOUNTAIN SOLUTIONS TO THEIR FACILITY. SMOKY MOUNTAIN SOLUTIONS PUMPED THE CORROSIVE LIQUID BACK INTO TANKERS. PROPER SHIPPING DOCUMENTS WERE RECEIVED. DSSI SHIPPED THE TANKERS ONE AT A TIME TO THEIR FACILITY. THE PH WAS ADJUSTED TO NON-CORROSIVE LEVELS, AND RETURNED TO SMOKY MOUNTAIN SOLUTIONS FOR PROCESSING.
column169: SPRU REVISED PROCEDURES TO ENSURE PH WAS CHECKED, AND ADJUSTED AS NECESSARY PRIOR TO LOADING TANKERS.

column168: At approximately 1547-CT on 11/19/2016 the BNSF Service Interruption Desk was notified by a Mechanical Supervisor in Barstow, CA that car GATX 17174 was discovered to have a vapor release by an employee inspecting cars in the yard.  The employee stated that a very strong odor was coming from the GATX 17174. The car was a residue car that last contained Sodium Sulfide Solutions Spent, Containing Sodium Hydroxide (STCC 4936653).  The detectable odor by the residue in the car was caused by a deteriorated and defective manway gasket which was replaced by BNSF hazmat responders.  The car was properly secured and departed the terminal without further delay.  No car contamination or environmental clean up was required. No injuries were reported and no waterways were impacted.  The quantity released shown in item 19 is an estimated value.
column169: This was a preventable NAR which can be avoided with proper attention given to quality inspection and pre-trip processes at the loading/unloading terminal.  All primary and secondary closures including manway gaskets should be inspected and replaced if found defective.  Follow up audits and retraining of employees is recommended for all personnel involved in the loading and unloading of tank cars.

column168: LT HARNETT TRUCKING’S SEMI TANK TRAILER WAS SB ON US 23 SOUTH BLOOMFIELD, OHIO STOPPING AND STARTING AT A SERIES OF TRAFFIC LIGHTS. WHILE ACCELERATION FROM A STOP AT ONE OF THE TRAFFIC SIGNALS THE PRODUCT SURGED IN THE STRAIGHT BORE TANK TRAILER. THE SURGING MOTION OF THE LIQUID RESIN MATERIAL TO THE BACK OF THE TANK PUSHED OUT THE FUSIBLE CAP DISC AT THE REAR 3” CLEAN-OUT PORT SPILLING OUT THE LIQUID RESIN SOLUTION ONTO THE REAR-END OF THE TANKER AND ALSO SPATTERING VEHICLES (TWO) WHILE MOVING SB ON US-23. THE WEATHER CONDITIONS AT THE TIME WAS A HEAVY RAIN DOWN POURING.     THE TRUCK TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 4 MILES BEFORE STOPPED BY A STATE TROOPER AT MP # 11, US-23 ON A CONNECTOR ROAD, NO NAME. THE PICKAWAY TWP FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED DUE TO CLASS 3 MATERIAL. THE MATERIAL SPILLED ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER HAD SET UP INTO A SEMI SOLID TO SOLID MATERIAL, LIKE SHEETS OF PLASTIC.     L T HARNETT TRUCKING COMPANY PERSONNEL RESPONDED WITH MATERIALS TO REMOVE THE MATERIAL FROM THE TRAILER’S EXTERIOR. DUE TO THE 30 DEGREE OUTSIDE TEMPERATURES THE RESIN WAS IN AN EXTREMELY THICK SATE TO BEING IN THIN SOLID SHEETS. THE RESIN HAD TO BE SCRAPED OFF AND PUT INTO CONTAINERS FOR DISPOSAL AT THE DANA TANK WASH, GROVE CITY, OHIO.     THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED AFTER THE RESIN WAS CLEANED TO A STICKY TO SOLID STATE. IT WAS TAKEN TO THE DANA TANK WASH FOR FURTHER CLEANING IN IN THEIR TANK WASH BOY.     APPROXIMATELY 7 GALLONS WAS LOST IN THE DISCHARGE.     FAILURE WAS CAUSED BY THE MATERIAL SURGE AGAINST THE GIRARD 3SPF FUSIBLE CAP CAUSING THE DISC TO BREAK OUT. THE CAP WAS ON THE REAR 3” CLEAN OUT PORT ON THE TRAILER. THE LAST VIK TEST WAS 10-13-16.
column169: RELOCATED ALL FUSIBLE CAPS INTO MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER WHERE THERE IS LESS UPWARD FORCE WHEN THE SURGE OCCURRED.     DRIVER STABILITY IS BETTER AT THE CENTER OF THE TANK. IT IS A MORE STABLE PLATFORM WHERE THE DRIVER CAN INSPECT THE FUSIBLE CAP WITHOUT THE FEAR OF FALLING OFF THE NARROW CATWALK AT THE ENDS OF THE TANK.    CLEANING PLANTS HAVE BEEN REQUESTED NOT TO USE A HAMMER TO TIGHTEN THE CAPS AND TO HAND TIGHTEN WITH A SPANNER WENCH.     SPANNER WRENCHES HAVE BEEN ISSUED TO ALL DRIVER TO US ON THE CLEAN OUT CAPS.     A MAINTENANCE ALERT SENT OUT TO ALL SHOPS FOR SPECIAL ATTENTION GIVEN TO THE FUSIBLE CAPS DURING ANNUAL HM AND 60 DAY HM INSPECTIONS.

column168: Tandem axle tanker traveling downgrade on Route 800, was turning right onto Route 26 at too high of speed, high center of gravity combined with centrifugal force caused truck to roll over onto left side, sliding into guard rail and rest on it's left side(driver side). Fuel seeped from the lids of each of the four compartments. Ratchet straps and cribbing were applied to each lid to stop seeping. Trench was dug by hand where absorbent materials were laid to absorb fuel. Incident took place at the edge of an embankment, some fuel made it to foot of hill but no fuel entered waters of the State. Contractor removed soil and repaired site per instruction of the Ohio EPA on scene coordinator. tanker was drilled and fuel removed before up righting by wrecker.
column169: A plan has been put into place by management to hire a driver supervisor for this division (gas well fuel tendering) to increase training frequency, screen drivers, and coordinate deliveries.

column168: Cabin Senior before leaving for her legal rest (approximately 3 hours into the AUH-ORD sector) brought her company iPad to the Cabin Manager (CM). The iPad was extremely hot and curved/bent. She mentioned that it had been kept on the galley top when she noticed the overheating. Captain was informed. The iPad was taken to the R1 galley and its cover was removed. CM tried to cool the device by using a bag of ice cubes covered with a napkin, however, as one part cooled, the heating could still be felt spreading to the other parts. Captain instructed that the device to be submerged fully in the water. Crew followed captain’s instructions and device remained submerged in the water until landing. After landing in ORD the device was handed over to the ORD ground staff.
column169: Crew members have been trained in the management of electronic devices indicating signs of overheating.

column25: NEW YORK STATE ELECTRIC & GAS CORPORATION
column168: We sent an environmental service cleanup crew to respond to a motor vehicle accident where several transformers on a utility pole were knocked to the ground. At the cleanup, the crew removed all the PCB oils from the transformers, and filled the emptied transformer casings with absorbents to solidify any remaining oil residue. One of transformer lids was bent slightly, and could not provide a tight seal with its gasket. The transformers were not placed in approved UN rated plastic transformer bags or over pack drum. Our crew transported these waste transformers back to the branch, where they would be placed in temporary containment/storage till shipped to the final destination.  While in containment/temporary storage at the branch, the transformers were incorrectly placed on their sides, not upright. This, combined with the bent lid, led to a small leak of unabsorbed transformer oil. The leakage was reported the next morning, where facility personnel then donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, and remediated the small spill using absorbent pads and granulated absorbent material. The generated waste from the cleanup was placed in an already manifested PCB containing waste drum from the original emergency cleanup event. The spill was reported to the reported to New York State DEC at 13:40 11/23/16, report # 1608209, operator #585 David.
column169: We have retrained the crew, driver, and facility personnel in the correct way to prepare waste transformers for transit, the correct UN rated packaging for transformers and when they need to use it, and the correct way to store waste transformers. We have also retrained the crew to more carefully inspect potentially damaged transformers before shipping, so that the correct UN rated packaging can be used when needed.

The legs of the tote are integral to the tote so when the forklift going in to pick up the tote it hit one of the legs which in turn fractured the body of the tote causing leakage.
column169: A better design tote would not have had body damage when a leg ids hit. Legs of totes and pallets are subject to unintentional bumps and should be able to withstand the contact without compromising the integrity of the body of the tote.

column168: ONE TUESDAY NOVEMBER 29, AT APPROXIMATELY 11:15 AM, AN AIRGAS SPECIALTY PRODUCTS WAREHOUSE EMPLOYEE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF DISCONNECTING THE LOADING HOSE FROM THE AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE TRAILER BEING FILLED. AS THE EMPLOYEE DISCONNECTED THE CAM-LOC CONNECTION, AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE GUSHED FROM THE HOSE CONNECTION. A CO-WORKER WAS NEAR THE INCIDENT LOCATION AND WAS ABLE TO CLOSE THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THE TRAILER STOPPING THE FLOW OF PRODUCT AND IMMEDIATELY STARTED WASHING THE AREA WITH WATER. IT APPEARS THE EMPLOYEE CLOSED THE HOSE END VALVE ON THE LOADING HOSE CONNECTED TO THE STORAGE TANKS BUT DID NOT CLOSE THE MAIN TANK VALVE ON THE TANKER RELEASING A 2” STREAM OF 19% @ 10 PSIG APPROXIMATELY 93 GALLONS OF 19.4% AQUA, FOR APPROXIMATELY 5 TO 6 SECONDS.
column169: REFRESHER TRAINING ON COMPANY SOP FOR LOADING AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE TANKERS.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: On November 28, 2016 at 0625 ET, during unloading operations, terminal personnel accidentally punctured a UN2794 Wet Filled Battery "Battery" during a forklift accident. Approximately 1-ounces released to the trailer floor. No waterways, soils, and drains were reported to have been impacted. The terminal personnel utilized granular absorbents to contain and clean the release. The absorbents used to clean the release were placed (1) 5-gallon poly drum and staged in OS&D. The battery was also staged in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: WHILE OUT ON CITY DELIVERIES, DISCOVERED LEAKING DRUM. CERTIFIED CONTRACTOR PLACED DRUM INTO LINED SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER. SPILLAGE NEUTRALIZED AND MANAGED PROPERLY REMAINDER OF SHIPMENT DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE.
column169: TERMINAL MANAGEMENT SHOULD REVIEW USE THIS INCIDENT AS A REFRESHER ON ENSURING DRUMMED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARE PROTECTED FROM PROTRUSIONS.

column168: AT 1:15 PM ON NOVEMBER 21, 2016 OUR FUEL TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS STOPPED AT THE INTERSECTION OF MAIN STREET AND AIRPORT ROAD IN THE HEIGHTS OF BILLINGS, MONTANA HEADING NORTH. AT THE GREEN ARROW, DRIVER TURNED LEFT HEADING WEST ON AIRPORT ROAD. AT THE CONCLUSION OF THE TURN, THE SECOND PUP TRAILER (P40) TIPPED OVER. THE IMPACT CAUSED A CRACK IN THE COMPARTMENTS CARRYING DIESEL FUEL. THE CRACK WAS AT THE TOP RIGHT SIDE ABOUT 4 FEET FROM THE FRONT.   THE DIESEL FUEL SPILLED OUT ON THE ASPHALT OF AIRPORT ROAD. 911 WAS CALLED. THE CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED ALONG WITH A FOAM TRUCK FROM THE NEARBY LOGAN AIRPORT. FUEL RETARDANT FOAM WAS DISPERSED ON THE SPILLED DIESEL FUEL ON THE ROADWAY. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PACKED THE NEARBY STORM DRAIN WITH SAND BAGS AND DIRT. THE LEAK LASTED ABOUT ONE AND A HALF HOURS. THE CLEANUP WAS CONDUCTED BY HANSER'S.   THE TRAILER WAS CARRYING 1400 GALLONS IN ONE COMPARTMENT AND 1600 GALLONS IN THE OTHER COMPARTMENT. 1522 GALLONS OF DIESEL SPILLED WITH 8 TO 10 GALLONS DOWN THE NEARBY STORM DRAIN. THE DIESEL FUEL WAS COLLECTED AND CLEANED FROM THE CONTAINMENT AREA OF THE STORM DRAIN PREVENTING RUN OFF TO THE NEARBY STAGNATE ALKALI CREEK. THE REMAINING 1478 GALLONS WERE PUMPED OFF AND TAKEN TO OUR BULK FUEL PLANT.
column169: OPERATOR ERROR WAS DETERMINED AS THE FACTOR CAUSING THE INCIDENT. EACH DRIVER IS CURRENTLY GIVEN A ROAD TEST BY A QUALIFIED DRIVER TRAINER TO ENSURE THE NEW DRIVER IS CHECKED OFF TO DRIVE SOLO. ADDITIONALLY, EACH NEW DRIVER IS TESTED ON SAFETY VIDEOS TO INCLUDE TRANSPORT ROLL OVER. THIS DRIVER WAS TESTED ON SEPTEMBER 15, 2016. CONTINUED EFFORT AND TRAINING WILL BE DONE FOR CURRENT AND FUTURE DRIVERS TO ENSURE THEY UNDERSTAND THE FACTORS OF VEHICLE ROLL-OVER.

column42: FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTIONS, WITH NOT LESS THAN 25 PERCENT FORMALDEHYDE
column168: A First Class Transport tractor trailer was involved in a multiple vehicle rollover accident resulting in the release of approximately 2 gallons of UN2209 Urea Formaldehyde Concentrate. The material leaked from a washout cap on the cargo tank (307) while it was over turned. The release impacted the soil median. An environmental contractor responded and utilized a betts emergency unloading valve to trans-load the product into a relief tanker provided by the carrier. The impacted soil was removed and containerized for proper disposal.

column168: Aircraft N436QX, operating as Horizon Air flight 2544/01NOV, departed PDX 04:53 L arrived SEA 05:39 L.  After receiving a package off the flight, Horizon Seattle Stores discovered a 9-pound box contained an Emergency Locator Transmitter and contacted their leadership in Portland.  This item is properly classified as UN 3091, lithium metal batteries contained in equipment, class 9. There is a 12 gram Section I lithium metal battery inside the ELT.  The item was properly prepared for road transport, and was intended to travel via ground.    There was no release. The 12 gram lithium content of the ELT is provided for additional classification information only.
column169: Horizon Stores immediately began their investigation to determine root cause, contributing factors and will determine appropriate corrective actions.

column168: Truck Driver was driving north on Michigan Hwy 196. Truck driver exited highway at the 109th street exit ramp. Driver failed to slow down adequately for the exit ramp which caused him to flip the cargo tank trailer when he turned the unit. Driver was hauling unleaded gasoline which caught fire and was left to burn out. The Michigan department of Environmental Quality was in charge of the clean up response.
column169: We feel the best way to prevent this incident from ever happening again is to offer a more detailed training on the dynamics of hauling a tanker. We have implemented a safety training that uses a combination of discussion, video (modeling centrifugal force, slosh/surge, proper ramp speed), and a driving test that focuses on the potential for roll overs to occur.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER LEFT THE SEARSPORT, ME MARINE TERMINAL AT 17:15 TO MAKE A DELIVERY TO THE FAIRFIELD CIRCLE K ON 227 MAIN STREET, HE DROVE SOUTH ON RTE 1 TO RTE 137, HEADING TO ALBION, FROM THERE, HE TURNED ONTO THE BENTON RD, AND PROCEEDED WEST TO BENTON. JUST OUTSIDE OF FAIRFIELD, THE DRIVER NOTICED WHAT APPEARED TO BE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER, WHEN IT WAS SAFE TO DO SO, HE PULLED OVER, THIS POINT THE FAIRFIELD POLICE WERE BEHIND HIM, AND THEIR BLUE LIGHTS WERE FLASHING, THEY HAD APPARENTLY RECEIVED REPORTS OF THE LEAK. ONCE THE DRIVER NOTICED THE LEAK, IT WAS HIS INTENT TO AVOID STOPPING NEAR PRIVATE PROPERTY AND THE KENEBECK RIVER. ONCE STOPPED, THE DRIVER SHUT THE TRUCK OFF, GRABBED A COPY OF THE BOL, AND PLACED THE REMAINING 2 COPIES ON THE DRIVER'S SEAT, HE GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK, CHOCKED THE WHEELS. THE FAIRFIELD POLICE HAD ALREADY CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS. THE OFFICER ASSISTED BY SHUTTING DOWN THE STREET AND KEEPING PEOPLE AWAY FROM THE AREA WHILE THE DRIVER DEPLOYED SPILL PADS AND THE EMERGENCY SPILL KIT. THE DRIVER ENSURED THAT EVERYONE WAS AWARE OF THE DANGER OF THE SITUATION. THE DRIVER HAD NO MEANS TO PLUG THE HOLE WITHOUT PUTTING HIMSELF OR OTHERS AT RISK, SO HE FOCUSED HIS EFFORTS ON CONTAINING THE SPILL, ONCE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED, THEY TOOK COMMAND OF THE SCENE, AND THE DRIVER ASSISTED AS NEEDED. ONCE THE HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED, THEY PLUGGED THE HOLE AND STOPPED THE FLOW PRODUCT. DURING ALL THE ACTIVITY, IT WAS APPARENT TO THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL THAT SOMEONE SHOT THE TRAILER. ONCE THE SITUATION WAS UNDER CONTROL, THE TRUCK WAS MOVED TO THE CIRCLE K STATE ON 227 MAIN STREET AND COMPARTMENT #4 (THE COMPARTMENT WITH THE BULLET HOLE) WAS UNLOADED. USING THE STORES ELECTRONIC INVENTORY SYSTEMS WE WERE ABLE TO GET ACCURATE READINGS TO DETERMINE THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT WAS LOST DUE TO THE LEAK (150 GALLONS OF GASOLINE). ONCE THE COMPARTMENT WAS DRAINED, THE INVESTIGATING STATE POLICE OFFICER WAS ABLE TO RETRIEVE THE BULLET.
column169: WE WILL BE HAVING MEETING WITH OUR DRIVERS TO DISCUSS, SECURITY AWARENESS, BUT IN THIS PARTICULAR INSTANCE, IT MORE THAN LIKELY WOULDN'T HAVE MADE A DIFFERENCE, AS IT WAS DARK, RAINING HARD AND IT MAY HAVE BEEN A DRIVE BY SHOOTING.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING 300-GALLON TOTE WAS FOUND TURNED OVER AND LEAKING. MILKCO PERSONNEL DEPLOYED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN THE FREE LIQUID. THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND MOUNTAIN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. (MESI) WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. MESI ARRIVED AND INSPECTED THE TRAILER AND TOTE WEARING THE APPROPRIATE PPE. MESI DETERMINED THAT THE VENT CAP OF THE TOTE WAS LEAKING. MESI PROCEEDED TO UPRIGHT THE LEAKING TOTE. MESI DEPLOYED ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIAL AS NEEDED. MESI RECOVERED THE SPENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL. MESI TRANSPORTED THE WASTE TO THEIR FACILITY PENDING DISPOSAL COORDINATION.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, WILSON TRUCKING CORPORATION WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: Driver came around a corner on WV-92N and found a WV Highways truck stopped in the lane due to a downed power line. Buckets were placed immediately to collect and contain the spill of 20 gallons.  The area was baled off within thirty minutes.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON I-81 WHEN ANOTHER VEHICLE TRAVELING NORTH, PULLING A UTILITY TRAILER. THE UTILITY TRAILER WENT UNDER OUR TRUCK CASING THE TRUCK TO JACK-KNIFE AND OVER TURN AT WHICH TIME IT CAUGHT FIRE AND EXPLODED. EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WAS CALLED IN FROM GREEN TWP AND SURROUNDING AREAS. MY COMPANY WAS NOTIFIED APPROXIMATELY 10 HOURS AFTER THE ACCIDENT. MY DRIVER WAS KILLED. EFFORTS BY THE PA. STATE POLICE HAVE NOT BEEN ABLE TO IDENTITY THE PARTY THAT WAS PULLING THE UTILITY TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS STOLEN.     THE ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCT SERVICES OF VERMONT, INC. AND PATRIOUT ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WAS HIRED FOR CLEANUP.
column169: THIS WAS A FREAK ACCIDENT AND I AM NOT SURE WHAT STEPS COULD BE TAKEN TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING.
